\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb240\sl260\slmult0\ql\ltrch\loch {\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 Summary}
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb240\sl260\slmult0\qj\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 An employee whose religion required him to observe his Sabbath day on Saturday, was discharged when he refused to work on Saturdays. Although the employee had earlier held a job with the employer where the employee had sufficient seniority to allow him to avoid Saturday work, when the employee sought and received a transfer to a different job with the employer, the employee was placed near the bottom of a new seniority list. Due to his low seniority on the new job, the employee was called upon to work on Saturdays. Although the employer agreed to permit the union to seek a change of work assignments for the employee, the union was unwilling to violate the seniority provisions of the collective bargaining agreement. The employer refused to unilaterally violate the seniority provisions and also refused to allow the employee to work only 4 days a week, since this would have required either (1) filling his position with a supervisor or an employee from another area and would have undermanned another operation, or (2) employing someone not regularly assigned to work Saturdays, thus requiring the payment of premium wages. Following his discharge, the employee brought an action for injunctive relief in the United States District Court for the Western District of Missouri, alleging that his discharge constituted religious discrimination in violatio of 703(a)(1) of Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964 (}{\f6\fs28\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 42 USCS 2000e-2(a)(1)}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 ). The District Court ruled in favor of the employer and the union (}{\f6\fs28\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 375 F Supp 877}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 ), but the United States Court of Appeals for the Eighth Circuit reversed the judgment in favor of the employer, holding that the employer had not satisfied its duty to accommodate the religious needs of the employee (}{\f6\fs28\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 527 F2d 33}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 ).}
\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 On certiorari, the United States Supreme Court reversed. In an opinion by White, J., joined by Burger, Ch. J., and Stewart, Blackmun, Powell, Rehnquist, and Stevens, JJ., it was held that (1) the employer had made reasonable efforts to accommodate the religious needs of the employee, (2) the employer was not required to violate the collective bargaining agreement to accommodate the employee by violating the seniority system which was not shown to have a discriminatory purpose, and (3) the alternative plans, which would have permitted the employee to avoid Saturday work by working only 4 days per week, constituted an undue hardship on the employer.}
\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 Marshall, J., joined by Brennan, J., dissented, expressing the view that the employer did not prove that it exhausted all reasonable accommodations and that the only remaining alternatives would have caused undue hardship on the employer's business.  }
