\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb240\sl260\slmult0\qj\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 Judgment entered by an equally divided court is not entitled to precedential weight.}
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb240\sl260\slmult0\ql\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 \line }
\par\plain {\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1  RIGHTS \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u167\'A77.5 \~>\~employment discrimination -- religion -- definition -- \~>\~Headnote:}{\f0\fs24 \line }{\f4\fs28\b1\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 LEdHN[3]}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  [3]}
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb240\sl260\slmult0\qj\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 The intent and effect of the definition of "religion" included in the 1972 Amendments to Title VII, 701(j), of the Civil Rights Act of 1964 (}{\f6\fs28\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 42 USCS 2000e(j)}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 ), is to make it an unlawful employment practice under 703(a)(1) of the Act (}{\f6\fs28\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 42 USCS 2000e-2(a)(1)}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 )--which makes it an unlawful employment practice to discriminate in employment on the basis of religion--for an employer not to make reasonable accommodations, short of undue hardship, for the religious practices of his employees and prospective employees.}
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb240\sl260\slmult0\ql\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 \line }
\par\plain {\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1  RIGHTS \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u167\'A74.4 \~>\~ STATUTES \u167\'A7158.6\~>\~religious discrimination -- EEOC Guidelines -- \~>\~Headnote:}{\f0\fs24 \line }{\f4\fs28\b1\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 LEdHN[4A]}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  [4A]}{\f4\fs28\b1\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 LEdHN[4B]}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  [4B]}
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb240\sl260\slmult0\qj\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 Although ordinarily an Equal Employment Opportunity Commission guideline--such as one requiring employers to make reasonable accommodations to the religious needs of their employees and prospective employees where such accommodation can be made without undue hardship on the conduct of the employer's business--is not entitled to great weight where it varies from prior Commission policy and no new legislative history has been introduced in support of the change, nevertheless, where Congress has not just kept its silence by refusing to overturn the administrative construction, but has ratified it with positive legislation, the guideline is entitled to some deference; it is at least sufficient to warrant the court's accepting the guideline as a defensible construction of the statute, prior to its amendment, as imposing upon an employer the duty of reasonable accommodation in the absence of undue hardship.}
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb240\sl260\slmult0\ql\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 \line }
\par\plain {\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1  RIGHTS \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u167\'A77.5 \~>\~religious discrimination -- hardship on employer -- \~>\~Headnote:}{\f0\fs24 \line }{\f4\fs28\b1\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 LEdHN[5A]}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  [5A]}{\f4\fs28\b1\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 LEdHN[5B]}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  [5B]}{\f4\fs28\b1\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 LEdHN[5C]}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  [5C]}
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb240\sl260\slmult0\qj\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 An employer who discharged an employee who refused to work on Saturday, his Sabbath day, did not violate 703(a)(1) of Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964--which makes it an unlawful employment practice to discriminate in employment on the basis of religion--by not, in the alternative, (1) permitting the employee to work a 4-day week, utilizing in his place a supervisor or other worker on duty elsewhere, (2) filling the employee's Sabbath day shift from other available personnel competent to do the job, or (3) arranging a swap with another employee either for another shift or for the Sabbath days, since the employer made reasonable efforts to accommodate the employee and each of the alternatives would have been an undue hardship within the meaning of the statute as construed by the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission guidelines--which provided that employers must make reasonable accommodations to the religious needs of employees and prospective employees where such accommodation can be made without undue hardship on the conduct of the employer's business--in that (1) as to the first alternative, the employer would have been required to replace the employee with supervisory personnel or with qualified personnel from other departments which would mean lost efficiency in other jobs, (2) as to the second alternative, the employer would have been required to replace the employee with other available employees at premium wages, and (3) as to the third alternative, both the union and the employer had agreed to the seniority system, the union was unwilling to entertain a variance over the objections of men senior to the employee in question, and for the employer to have arranged unilaterally for a swap would have amounted to a breach of the collective bargaining agreement. (Marshall and Brennan, JJ., dissented from this holding.)}
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb240\sl260\slmult0\ql\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 \line }
\par\plain {\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1  RIGHTS \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u167\'A77.5 \~>\~seniority system -- \~>\~Headnote:}{\f0\fs24 \line }{\f4\fs28\b1\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 LEdHN[6]}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  [6]}
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb240\sl260\slmult0\qj\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 A seniority system under which the most senior employees have first choice of job and shift assignments, and the most junior employees are required to work when the union steward is unable to find enough people willing to work at a particular time or in a particular job to fill the employer's needs, represents, under 703(a)(1) of Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964 (}{\f6\fs28\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 42 USCS 2000e-2(a)(1)}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 )--which makes it an unlawful employment practice to discriminate in employment on the basis of religion--a significant accommodation to the needs, both religious and secular, of all of the employer's employees.}
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb240\sl260\slmult0\ql\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 \line }
\par\plain {\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1  RIGHTS \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u167\'A77.5 \~>\~seniority system -- \~>\~Headnote:}{\f0\fs24 \line }{\f4\fs28\b1\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 LEdHN[7A]}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  [7A]}{\f4\fs28\b1\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 LEdHN[7B]}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  [7B]}
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb240\sl260\slmult0\qj\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 Although neither a collective bargaining contract nor a seniority system may be employed to violate 703(a)(1) of Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964 (}{\f6\fs28\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 42 USCS 2000e-2(a)(1)}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 ), which makes it an unlawful employment practice to discriminate in employment on the basis of religion, nevertheless, the duty under that statute to accommodate an employee's religious needs does not require the employer to take steps inconsistent with the otherwise valid agreement; in the absence of a clear and express indication to that effect from Congress, it will not be held that an agreed-upon seniority system must give way when necessary to accommodate religious observances; an employer is not required by Title VII to carve out a special exception to its seniority system in order to help an employee to meet his religious obligations.}
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb240\sl260\slmult0\ql\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 \line }
\par\plain {\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1  RIGHTS \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u167\'A77.5 \~>\~employment -- reasonable accommodation of religious needs -- \~>\~Headnote:}{\f0\fs24 \line }{\f4\fs28\b1\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 LEdHN[8]}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  [8]}
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb240\sl260\slmult0\qj\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 Under 703(a)(1) of Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964 (}{\f6\fs28\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 42 USCS 2000e-2(a)(1)}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 ), which makes it an unfair employment practice to discriminate in employment on the basis of religion, an employer, in order to satisfy his duty to make reasonable accommodations to the religious needs of his employees, is not required to deny the shift and job preference of some employees, as well as deprive them of their contractual rights, in order to accommodate or prefer the religious needs of others.}
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb240\sl260\slmult0\ql\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 \line }
\par\plain {\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1  RIGHTS \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u167\'A77.5 \~>\~discriminatory employment practice -- seniority system -- \~>\~Headnote:}{\f0\fs24 \line }{\f4\fs28\b1\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 LEdHN[9]}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  [9]}
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb240\sl260\slmult0\qj\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 The purpose of 703(h) of Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964 (}{\f6\fs28\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 42 USCS 2000e-2(h)}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 ), which provides that it shall not be an unlawful employment practice for an employer to apply different conditions of employment pursuant to a bona fide seniority system, is to make clear that the routine application of a bona fide seniority system would not be unlawful under Title VII; 703(h) is a definitional provision, and as with other provisions of 703, subsection (h) delineates which employment practices are illegal and thereby prohibited and which are not.}
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb240\sl260\slmult0\ql\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 \line }
\par\plain {\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1  RIGHTS \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u167\'A77.5 \~>\~discriminatory employment practice -- seniority system -- \~>\~Headnote:}{\f0\fs24 \line }{\f4\fs28\b1\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 LEdHN[10]}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  [10]}
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb240\sl260\slmult0\qj\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 Absent a discriminatory purpose, the operation of a seniority system cannot be an unlawful employment practice prohibited by 703(a)(1) of Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964 (}{\f6\fs28\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 42 USCS 2000e-2(a)(1)}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 ), which makes it an unlawful employment practice to discriminate in employment because of race, color, religion, sex, or national origin, even if the system has some discriminatory consequences.}
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb240\sl260\slmult0\ql\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 \line }
\par\plain {\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1  RIGHTS \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u167\'A77.5 \~>\~unlawful employment practice -- seniority system -- intent -- \~>\~Headnote:}{\f0\fs24 \line }{\f4\fs28\b1\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 LEdHN[11A]}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  [11A]}{\f4\fs28\b1\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 LEdHN[11B]}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  [11B]}
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb240\sl260\slmult0\qj\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 Since 703(h) of Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964 (}{\f6\fs28\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 42 USCS 2000e-2(h)}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 ), which provides that it shall not be an unlawful employment practice for an employer to apply different conditions of employment pursuant to a bona fide seniority system, unequivocally mandates that there is no statutory violation of 703(a)(1) of Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964 (}{\f6\fs28\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 42 USCS 2000e-2(a)(1)}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 )--which makes it an unlawful employment practice to discriminate in employment because of race, color, religion, sex, or national origin--in the absence of a showing of discriminatory purpose, the operation of a seniority system itself cannot be an unlawful employment practice unless a discriminatory purpose is shown.}
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb240\sl260\slmult0\ql\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 \line }
\par\plain {\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1  RIGHTS \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u167\'A77.5 \~>\~accommodation of employee's religious needs -- expense -- \~>\~Headnote:}{\f0\fs24 \line }{\f4\fs28\b1\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 LEdHN[12A]}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  [12A]}{\f4\fs28\b1\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 LEdHN[12B]}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  [12B]}
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb240\sl260\slmult0\qj\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 Section 703(a)(1) of Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964 (}{\f6\fs28\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 42 USCS 2000e-2(a)(1)}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 ), which makes it an unlawful employment practice to discriminate in employment on the basis of religion, does not require an employer to accommodate the religious needs of an employee where substantial expenditures are required to do so.}
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb240\sl260\slmult0\ql\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 \line }
\par\plain {\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1  RIGHTS \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u167\'A77.5 \~>\~accommodation of employee's religious needs -- undue hardship -- \~>\~Headnote:}{\f0\fs24 \line }{\f4\fs28\b1\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 LEdHN[13]}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  [13]}
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb240\sl260\slmult0\qj\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 To require an employer to bear more than a de minimis cost in order to give an employee his Sabbath days off is an undue hardship under an Equal Employment Opportunity Commission guideline which interpreted 703(a)(1) of Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964--which makes it an unlawful employment practice to discriminate in employment on the basis of religion--as requiring employers to make reasonable accommodations to the religious needs of employees and prospective employees where such accommodation can be made without undue hardship on the conduct of the employer's business; to require an employer to bear additional costs when no such costs are incurred to give other employees the days off that they want would involve unequal treatment of employees on the basis of their religion.}
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb240\sl260\slmult0\ql\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 \line }
\par\plain {\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1  RIGHTS \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u167\'A77.5 \~>\~employment discrimination -- \~>\~Headnote:}{\f0\fs24 \line }{\f4\fs28\b1\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 LEdHN[14]}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  [14]}
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb240\sl260\slmult0\qj\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 Since the paramount concern of Congress in enacting Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964 (}{\f6\fs28\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 42 USCS 2000e et seq.}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 ) was the elimination of discrimination in employment, in the absence of clear statutory language or legislative history to the contrary, the statute will not be construed to require an employer to discriminate against some employees in order to enable others to observe their Sabbath.  }
