\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb240\sl260\slmult0\qj\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 Section 703(a)(1) of the Civil Rights Act of 1964, Title VII, 78 Stat. 255, }{\f6\fs28\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 42 U.S.C.  \loch\af6\hich\af6\dbch\af6\uc1\u167\'A7 2000e-2(a)(1)}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 , makes it an unlawful employment practice for an employer to discriminate against an employee or a prospective employee on the basis of his or her religion. At the time of the events involved here, a guideline of the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission (EEOC), }{\f6\fs28\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 29 CFR \loch\af6\hich\af6\dbch\af6\uc1\u167\'A7 1605.1(b) (1968)}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 , required, as the Act itself now does, }{\f6\fs28\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 42 U.S.C.  \loch\af6\hich\af6\dbch\af6\uc1\u167\'A7 2000e (j) (1970 ed., Supp. V)}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 , that an employer, short of "undue hardship," make "reasonable accommodations" to the religious needs of its employees.  The issue in this case is the extent of the employer's obligation under Title VII to accommodate an employee whose religious beliefs prohibit him from working on Saturdays.  }
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb200\sl260\slmult0\qj\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 I }
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb240\sl260\slmult0\qj\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 We summarize briefly the facts found by the Distirct}{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[****8]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  Court.  }{\f6\fs28\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 375 F.Supp. 877 (WD Mo. 1974)}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 . }
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb200\sl260\slmult0\qj\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 Petitioner Trans World Airlines (TWA) operates a large maintenance and overhaul base in Kansas City, Mo.  On June 5, 1967, respondent Larry G. Hardison was hired by TWA to work as a clerk in the Stores Department at its Kansas City base.  Because of its essential role in the Kansas City operation, the Stores Department must operate 24 hours per day, 365 days per year, and whenever an employee's job in that department is not filled, an employee must be }{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[*67]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  shifted from another department, or a supervisor must cover the job, even if the work in other areas may suffer.  }
\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 Hardison, like other employees at the Kansas City base, was subject to a seniority system contained in a collective-bargaining agreement }{\f1\fs24\super 1}
\par\pard\plain \ri0\ql\ltrch\loch \f0\fs24
\par\plain \f0\fs24
\par\plain {\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "scrivcmt://520A5F3C-7A6C-4058-B0AE-F95C0A0D1B58"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24 *}}{\f1\fs24\super  }{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  that TWA maintains with petitioner International Association of Machinists and Aerospace Workers (IAM).  }{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "scrivcmt://1D888535-5A02-4D6B-90C5-4E7412E455EA"}{\fldrslt\f1\fs24\super 2}}{\f1\fs24\super  }{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  The seniority system is implemented by the union steward through a system of bidding by employees for particular shift assignments as they become available.  The most senior employees have first choice for job and }{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[***121]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  shift assignments, and the most junior employees are required to work when the union steward}{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[****9]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  is unable to find enough people willing to work at a particular time or in a particular job to fill TWA's needs.  }
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb200\sl260\slmult0\qj\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 In the spring of 1968 Hardison began to study the religion known as the Worldwide Church of God.  One of the tenets of that religion is that one must observe the}{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[****10]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  Sabbath by refraining from performing any work from sunset on Friday until sunset on Saturday.  The religion also proscribes work on certain specified religious holidays. }
\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 When Hardison informed Everett Kussman, the manager of the Stores Department, of his religious conviction regarding }{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[*68]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  observance of the Sabbath, Kussman agreed that the union steward should seek a job swap for Hardison or a change of days off; that Hardison would have his religious holidays off whenever possible if Hardison agreed to work the traditional holidays when asked; and that Kussman would try to find Hardison another job that would be more compatible with his religious beliefs.  The problem was temporarily solved when Hardison transferred to the 11 p.m.-7 a.m. }{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[**2269]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  shift.  Working this shift permitted Hardison to observe his Sabbath.  }
\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 The problem soon reappeared when Hardison bid for and received a transfer from Building 1, where he had been employed, to Building 2, where he would work the day shift.  The two buildings had entirely separate seniority lists; and while in Building 1 Hardison had sufficient seniority to observe the Sabbath regularly, he was second from the bottom on the}{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[****11]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  Building 2 seniority list.  }
\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 In Building 2 Hardison was asked to work Saturdays when a fellow employee went on vacation.  TWA agreed to permit the union to seek a change of work assignments for Hardison, but the union was not willing to violate the seniority provisions set out in the collective-bargaining contract, }{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "scrivcmt://E3F9842E-33A5-4356-A4F6-D95D3600AC2D"}{\fldrslt\f1\fs24\super 3}}{\f1\fs24\super  }{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  and Hardison had insufficient seniority to bid for a shift having Saturdays off.  }
\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 A proposal that Hardison work only four days a week was rejected by the company.  Hardison's job was essential, and on weekends he was the only available person on his}{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[****12]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  shift to perform it.  To leave the position empty would have impaired supply shop functions, which were critical to airline operations; to fill Hardison's position with a supervisor or an }{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[*69]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  employee from another area would simply have undermanned another operation; and to employ someone not regularly assigned to work Saturdays would have required TWA to pay premium wages.  }
\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 When an accommodation was not reached, Hardison refused to report for work on Saturdays.  A transfer to the twilight shift proved unavailing since that schedule still required Hardison to work past sundown on Fridays.  After a hearing, Hardison }{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[***122]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  was discharged on grounds of insubordination for refusing to work during his designated shift.  }
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb240\sl260\slmult0\qj\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 Hardison, having first invoked the administrative remedy provided by Title VII, brought this action for injunctive relief in the United States District Court against TWA and IAM, claiming that his discharge by TWA constituted religious discrimination in violation of Title VII, }{\f6\fs28\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 42 U.S.C.  \loch\af6\hich\af6\dbch\af6\uc1\u167\'A7 2000e-2(a)(1)}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 .  He also charged that the union had discriminated against him by failing to represent him adequately in his dispute with TWA}{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[****13]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  and by depriving him of his right to exercise his religious beliefs.  Hardison's claim of religious discrimination rested on 1967 EEOC guidelines requiring employers "to make reasonable accommodations to the religious needs of employees" whenever such accommodation would not work an "undue hardship," }{\f6\fs28\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 29 CFR \loch\af6\hich\af6\dbch\af6\uc1\u167\'A7 1605.1 (1968)}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 , and on similar language adopted by Congress in the 1972 amendments to Title VII, }{\f6\fs28\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 42 U.S.C.  \loch\af6\hich\af6\dbch\af6\uc1\u167\'A7 2000e(j) (1970 ed., Supp. V)}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 .  }
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb200\sl260\slmult0\qj\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 After a bench trial, the District Court ruled in favor of the defendants.  Turning first to the claim against the union, the District Court ruled that although the 1967 EEOC guidelines were applicable to unions, the union's duty to accommodate Hardison's belief did not require it to ignore its seniority system as Hardison appeared to claim.  }{\f1\fs24\super 4}{\f6\fs18\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 \{\\Scrv_annot \\color=\{\\R=0.682353\\G=0.117647\\B=0.062745\} \\text=Establishment Clause of the First Amendment375 F.Supp. 877, 883 (WD Mo. 1974\\end_Scrv_annot\}}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "scrivcmt://D8A6EB82-2550-4459-9955-1677D361665F"}{\fldrslt\f6\fs18\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 )}}{\f1\fs24\super  }{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  As for Hardison's }{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[*70]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  claim against TWA, the District Court rejected at the outset TWA's contention that requiring it in any way to accommodate the religious needs of its employees would constitute an unconstitutional establishment of religion. As the District Court construed the Act, however, }{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[**2270]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  TWA had satisfied its "reasonable}{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[****14]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  accommodations" obligation, and any further accommodation would have worked an undue hardship on the company.}
\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 The Court of Appeals for the Eighth Circuit reversed the judgment for TWA.  }{\f6\fs28\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 527 F.2d 33 (1975)}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 . It agreed with the District Court's constitutional ruling, but held that TWA had not satisfied its duty to accommodate. Because it did not appear that Hardison had attacked directly the judgment in favor of the union, the Court of Appeals affirmed that judgment}{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[****15]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  without ruling on its substantive merits.  }
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb240\sl260\slmult0\qj\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 In separate petitions for certiorari TWA and IAM contended that adequate steps had been taken to accommodate Hardison's religious observances and that to construe the statute to require further efforts at accommodation would create an establishment of religion contrary to the }{\f6\fs28\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 First Amendment of the Constitution}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 .  TWA also contended that the Court of Appeals improperly ignored the District Court's findings of fact.  }
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb200\sl260\slmult0\qj\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 We granted both petitions for certiorari.  }{\f6\fs28\b0\i1\cf1 429 U.S. 958 (1976)}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 . Because we agree with petitioners that their conduct was not a violation of Title }{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[***123]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  VII, }{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "scrivcmt://470541BD-F4A2-4F9F-AFCB-F3309A769BCC"}{\fldrslt\f1\fs24\super 5}}{\f1\fs24\super  }{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  we need not reach the other questions presented.  }
\par\plain {\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[****16]\~\~[*71]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1   II}
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb240\sl260\slmult0\qj\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  }{\f4\fs28\b1\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 LEdHN[1]}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  [1]The Court of Appeals found that TWA had committed an unlawful employment practice under \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u167\'A7 703(a)(1) of the Act, }{\f6\fs28\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 42 U.S.C.  \loch\af6\hich\af6\dbch\af6\uc1\u167\'A7 2000e-2(a)(1)}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 , which provides: S}
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb200\sl260\slmult0\qj\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 "(a) It shall be an unlawful employment practice for an employer - }
\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 "(1) to fail or refuse to hire or to discharge any individual, or otherwise to discriminate against any individual with respect to his compensation, terms, conditions, or privileges of employment, because of such individual's race, color, religion, sex, or national origin."I }
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\ql\ltrch\loch \f0\fs24
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb240\sl260\slmult0\qj\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 The emphasis of both the language and the legislative history of the statute is on eliminating discrimination in employment; similarly situated employees are not to be treated differently solely because they differ with respect to race, color, religion, sex, or national origin.  }{\f1\fs24\super 6}{\f6\fs18\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 \{\\Scrv_annot \\color=\{\\R=0.682353\\G=0.117647\\B=0.062745\} \\text=McDonald v. Santa Fe Trail Transportation Co., 427 U.S. 273, 278-279 (1976)Franks v. Bowman Transportation Co., 424 U.S. 747, 763 (1976)McDonnell Douglas Corp. v. Green, 411 U.S. 792, 800 (1973)Griggs v. Duke Power Co., 401 U.S. 424, 429-430 (1971)}
\par\pard\plain \ri0\ql\ltrch\loch {\f6\fs18\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 id., at \\end_Scrv_annot\}}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "scrivcmt://EDB36CB8-5844-4E66-B395-F8EBDEE3C28E"}{\fldrslt\f6\fs18\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 58}}{\f1\fs24\super  }{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  This is true regardless of whether }{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[*72]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  the discrimination is directed against majorities or minorities.  }{\f6\fs28\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 McDonald v. Santa Fe Trail Transportation Co., 427 U.S. 273, 280 (1976)}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 .}{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[****17]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  See }{\f6\fs28\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 Griggs v. Duke Power Co., 401 U.S. 424, 431 (1971)}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 .}
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb240\sl260\slmult0\qj\ltrch\loch {\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[****18]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  The prohibition against religious discrimination soon raised the question of whether }{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[**2271]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  it was impermissible under \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u167\'A7 703(a)(1) to discharge or refuse to hire a person who for religious reasons refused to work during the employer's normal workweek.  In 1966 an EEOC guideline dealing with this problem declared that an employer had an obligation under the statute "to accommodate to the reasonable religious needs of employees\u8230\'85 where such accommodation can be made without serious inconvenience to the conduct of the }{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[***124]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  business." }{\f6\fs28\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 29 CFR \loch\af6\hich\af6\dbch\af6\uc1\u167\'A7 1605.1 (1967)}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 .  }
\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 In 1967 the EEOC amended its guidelines to require employers "to make reasonable accommodations to the religious needs of employees and prospective employees where such accommodations can be made without undue hardship on the conduct of the employer's business." }{\f6\fs28\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 29 CFR \loch\af6\hich\af6\dbch\af6\uc1\u167\'A7 1605.1 (1968)}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 .  The EEOC did not suggest what sort of accommodations are "reasonable" or when hardship to an employer becomes "undue." }{\f1\fs24\super 7}{\f6\fs18\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 \{\\Scrv_annot \\color=\{\\R=0.682353\\G=0.117647\\B=0.062745\} \\text=29 CFR \loch\af6\hich\af6\dbch\af6\uc1\u167\'A7 1605.1 (1968\\end_Scrv_annot\}}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "scrivcmt://C71A82EE-9F5C-48EE-A0C9-9CC5A723DABE"}{\fldrslt\f6\fs18\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 )}}{\f1\fs24\super  }{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  }
\par\plain {\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[****19]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1   }{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[*73]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1   }{\f4\fs28\b1\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 LEdHN[2A]}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  [2A]This question -- the extent of the required accommodation - remained unsettled when this Court, in }{\f6\fs28\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 Dewey v. Reynolds Metals Co., 402 U.S. 689 (1971)}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 , affirmed by an equally divided Court the Sixth Circuit's decision in }{\f6\fs28\b0\i1\cf1 429 F.2d 324 (1970)}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 . The discharge of an employee who for religious reasons had refused to work on Sundays was there held by the Court of Appeals not to be an unlawful employment practice because the manner in which the employer allocated Sunday work assignments was discriminatory in neither its purpose nor effect; and consistent with the 1967 EEOC guidelines, the employer had made a reasonable accommodation of the employee's beliefs by giving him the opportunity to secure a replacement for his Sunday work.  }{\f1\fs24\super 8}{\f4\fs18\b1\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 \{\\Scrv_annot \\color=\{\\R=0.682353\\G=0.117647\\B=0.062745\} \\text=LEdHN[2B]}
\par\pard\plain \ri0\ql\ltrch\loch {\f6\fs18\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 Neil v. Biggers, 409 U.S. 188, 192 (1972)Alexander v. Gardner-Denver Co., 415 U.S. 36 (1974\\end_Scrv_annot\}}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "scrivcmt://DC1A2E56-C846-4C3C-8F33-BD8EA784F77B"}{\fldrslt\f6\fs18\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 )}}{\f1\fs24\super  }{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  }
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb240\sl260\slmult0\qj\ltrch\loch {\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[****20]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1   }{\f4\fs28\b1\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 LEdHN[3]}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  [3]In part "to resolve by legislation" some of the issues raised in Dewey, 118 Cong. Rec. 706 (1972) (remarks of Sen. Randolph), Congress included the following definition of religion in its 1972 amendments to Title VII: S}
\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 "The term 'religion' includes all aspects of religious observance and practice, as well as belief, unless an employer demonstrates that he is unable,o reasonably accommodate }{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[*74]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  to an employee's or prospective employee's religious observance or practice without undue }{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[***125]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  hardship on the conduct of the employer's business." \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u167\'A7 701(j), }{\f6\fs28\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 42 U.S.C.  \loch\af6\hich\af6\dbch\af6\uc1\u167\'A7 2000e(j) (1970 ed., Supp. V)}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 .I }
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb200\sl260\slmult0\qj\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 The intent and effect of this definition was to make it an unlawful employment practice under \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u167\'A7 703(a)(1) for an employer not to make reasonable accommodations, short }{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[**2272]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  of undue hardship, for the religious practices of his employees and prospective employees.  But like the EEOC guidelines, the statute provides no guidance for determining the degree of accommodation}{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[****21]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  that is required of an employer.  The brief legislative history of \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u167\'A7 701(j) is likewise of little assistance in this regard.  }{\f1\fs24\super 9}
