\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb200\sl260\slmult0\qj\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 MR. JUSTICE }{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 MARSHALL}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 , with whom MR. JUSTICE }{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 BRENNAN}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  joins, dissenting.  }
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb240\sl260\slmult0\qj\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 One of the most intractable problems arising under Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964, }{\f6\fs28\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 42 U.S.C.  \loch\af6\hich\af6\dbch\af6\uc1\u167\'A7 2000e et seq.}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 , has been whether an employer is guilty of religious discrimination when he discharges an employee (or refuses to hire a job applicant) because of the employee's religious practices.  Particularly troublesome has been the plight of adherents to minority faiths who do not observe the holy days on which most businesses are closed -- Sundays, Christmas, and Easter - but who need time off for their own days of religious observance. The Equal Employment Opportunity Commission has}{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[****39]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  grappled with this problem in two sets of regulations, and in a long line of decisions.  Initially the Commission concluded that an employer was "free under Title VII to establish a normal workweek\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8230\'85 generally applicable to all employees," and that an employee could not "demand any alteration in [his work schedule] to accommodate his religious needs." }{\f6\fs28\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 29 CFR \loch\af6\hich\af6\dbch\af6\uc1\u167\'A7\u167\'A7 1605.1 (a)(3)}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 , }{\f6\fs28\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 (b)(3) (1967)}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 .  Eventually, however, the Commission changed its view and decided that employers must reasonably accommodate such requested schedule changes except where "undue hardship" would result -- for example, "where the employee's needed work cannot be performed }{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[*86]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  by another employee of substantially similar qualifications during the period of absence." }{\f6\fs28\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 29 CFR \loch\af6\hich\af6\dbch\af6\uc1\u167\'A7 1605.1 (b) (1976)}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 .  }{\f1\fs24\super 1}{\f6\fs18\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 \{\\Scrv_annot \\color=\{\\R=0.682353\\G=0.117647\\B=0.062745\} \\text=\loch\af6\hich\af6\dbch\af6\uc1\u167\'A7 1605.1Section 1605.1\\end_Scrv_annot\}}
\par\plain {\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "scrivcmt://57DD2960-FF49-471D-8E38-06313B37AF7E"}{\fldrslt\f6\fs18\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 *}}{\f1\fs24\super  }{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  In }{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[**2278]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  amending Title VII in 1972 Congress confronted the same problem, and adopted the second position of the EEOC.  Pub. L. 92-261, \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u167\'A7 2(7), 86 Stat. 103, codified at }{\f6\fs28\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 42 U.S.C.  \loch\af6\hich\af6\dbch\af6\uc1\u167\'A7 2000e (j) (1970 ed., Supp. V)}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 .  Both before and after the 1972 amendment the lower courts have considered at length the circumstances in which employers}{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[****40]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  must accommodate the religious practices of employees, reaching what the Court correctly describes as conflicting results, ante, at 75 n. 10.  And on two occasions this Court has attempted to provide guidance to the lower courts, only to find ourselves evenly divided.  }{\f6\fs28\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 Parker Seal Co. v. Cummins, 429 U.S. 65 (1976)}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 ; }{\f6\fs28\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 Dewey v. Reynolds Metals Co., 402 U.S. 689 (1971)}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 .}
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb200\sl260\slmult0\qj\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 Today's decision deals a fatal blow to all efforts under Title VII to accommodate work requirements to religious practices.  The Court holds, in essence, that although the EEOC }{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[***133]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  regulations and the Act state that an employer must make reasonable adjustments in his work demands to take account of religious observances, the regulation and Act do not }{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[*87]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  really mean what they say.  An employer, the Court concludes, need not grant even the most minor special privilege to religious observers to enable them to follow their faith.  As a question of social policy, this result is deeply troubling, for a society that truly values religious pluralism cannot compel adherents of minority religions to make the cruel choice of surrendering their religion or their job.And as a matter of law}{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[****41]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  today's result is intolerable, for the Court adopts the very position that Congress expressly rejected in 1972, as if we were free to disregard congressional choices that a majority of this Court thinks unwise.  I therefore dissent.  }
\par\plain {\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[****42]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  I }
\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 With respect to each of the proposed accommodations to respondent Hardison's religious observances that the Court discusses, it ultimately notes that the accommodation would have required "unequal treatment," ante, at 81, 84-85, in favor of the religious observer. That is quite true.  But if an accommodation can be rejected simply because it involves preferential treatment, then the regulation and the statute, while brimming with "sound and fury," ultimately "signif[y] nothing." }
\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 The accommodation issue by definition arises only when a neutral rule of general applicability conflicts with the religious practices of a particular employee.  In some of the reported cases, the rule in question has governed work attire; in other cases it has required attendance at some religious function; in still other instances, it has compelled membership in a union; and in the largest class of cases, it has concerned work schedules.  }{\f1\fs24\super 2}{\f6\fs18\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 \{\\Scrv_annot \\color=\{\\R=0.682353\\G=0.117647\\B=0.062745\} \\text=22 ALR Fed. 580 (1975\\end_Scrv_annot\}}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "scrivcmt://D2B69506-9A49-49A2-A623-9B34EFEE7DBC"}{\fldrslt\f6\fs18\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 )}}{\f1\fs24\super  }{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  What all these cases have in common is an employee who could comply with the rule only by violating what the employee views as a religious commandment.  In each }{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[*88]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  instance, the question is whether the employee is to be exempt from the rule's demands. }{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[****43]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  To do so will always result in a privilege being "allocated according to religious beliefs," ante, at 85, unless }{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[**2279]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  the employer gratuitously decides to repeal the rule in toto. What the statute says, in plain words, is that such allocations are required unless "undue hardship" would result.  }
\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 The point is perhaps best made by considering a not altogether hypothetical example.  See CCH EEOC Decisions (1973) P 6180. Assume that an employer requires all employees to wear a particular type of hat at work in order to make the employees readily identifiable to customers.  Such a rule obviously does not, on its face, violate Title VII, and an employee who altered the uniform for reasons of teste could be discharged.  But a very different}{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[****44]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  question would be posed by the discharge of an employee who, for religious reasons, insisted on wearing over her hair a tightly fitted scarf }{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[***134]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  which was visible through the hat.  In such a case the employer could accommodate this religious practice without undue hardship -- or any hardship at all.  Yet as I understand the Court's analysis -- and nothing in the Court's response, ante, at 83 n. 14, 84 n. 15, is to the contrary - the accommodation would not be required because it would afford the privilege of wearing scarfs to a select few based on their religious beliefs.  The employee thus would have to give up either the religious practice or the job.  This, I submit, makes a mockery of the statute.  }
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb240\sl260\slmult0\qj\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 In reaching this result, the Court seems almost oblivious of the legislative history of the 1972 amendments to Title VII which is briefly recounted in the Court's opinion, ante, at 73-75.  That history is far more instructive than the Court allows.  After the EEOC promulgated its second set of guidelines requiring reasonable accommodations unless undue hardship would result, at least two courts issued decisions questioning, whether the guidelines were consistent with Title}{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[****45]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  VII.  }{\f6\fs28\b0\i1\cf1 Dewey v. Reynolds Metals Co., 429 F.2d 324 (CA6 1970)}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 , }{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[*89]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  aff'd by equally divided }{\f6\fs28\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 Court, 402 U.S. 689 (1971)}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 ; }{\f6\fs28\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 Riley v. Bendix Corp., 330 F.Supp. 583 (MD Fla. 1971)}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 , rev'd, }{\f6\fs28\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 464 F.2d 1113 (CA5 1972)}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 . These courts reasoned, in language strikingly similar to today's decision, that to excuse religious observers from neutral work rules would "discriminate against\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8230\'85 other employees" and "constitute unequal administration of the collective-bargaining agreement." }{\f6\fs28\b0\i1\cf1 Dewey v. Reynolds Metals Co., supra, at 330}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 . They therefore refused to equate "religious discrimination with failure to accommodate." }{\f6\fs28\b0\i1\cf1 429 F.2d at 335}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 . When Congress was reviewing Title VII in 1972, Senator Jennings Randolph informed the Congress of these decisions which, he said, had "clouded" the meaning of religious discrimination. 118 Cong. Rec. 706 (1972).  He introduced an amendment, tracking the language of the EEOC regulation, to make clear that Title VII requires religious accommodation, even though unequal treatment would result.  The primary purpose of the amendment, he explained, was to protect Saturday Sabbatarians like}{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[****46]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  himself from employers who refuse "to hire or to continue in employment employees whose religious practices rigidly require them to abstain from work in the nature of hire on particular days." }{\f6\fs28\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 Id., at 705}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 .  His amendment was unaminously approved by the Senate on a roll-call vote, }{\f6\fs28\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 id., at 731}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 , and was accepted by the Conference Committee, H.R. Rep. No. 92-899, p. 15 (1972); S. Rep. No. 92-681, p. 15 (1972), whose report was approved by both Houses, 118 Cong. Rec. 7169, 7573 (1972).  Yet the Court today, in rejecting any accommodation that involves preferential treatment, follows the Dewey decision in direct contravention of congressional intent.  }
\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 The Court's interpretation of the statute, by effectively nullifying it, has the singluar advantage of making consideration of petitioner's constitutional challenge unnecessary.  The Court does not even rationalize its construction on this ground, however, nor could it, since "resort to an alternative construction to avoid deciding a constitutional question is appropriate }{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[*90]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  only when such a course is 'fairly possible' or when the statute }{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[***135]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  provides a 'fair alternative' construction." }{\f6\fs28\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 Swain v. Pressley, 430 U.S. 372, 378 n. 11 }{\f4\fs28\b1\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 \~[**2280]\~}{\f6\fs28\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2  (1977)}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 .}{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[****47]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  Moreover, while important constitutional questions would be posed by interpreting the law to compel employers (or fellow employees) to incur substantial costs to aid the religious observer, }{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "scrivcmt://F7070832-8A0D-4750-8B52-CE53BC009A9B"}{\fldrslt\f1\fs24\super 3}}{\f1\fs24\super  }{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  not all accommodations are costly, and the constitutionality of the statute is not placed in serious doubt simply because it sometimes requires an exemption from a work rule.  Indeed, this Court has repeatedly found no }{\f6\fs28\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 Establishment Clause}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  problems in exempting religious observers from state-imposed duties, e.g., }{\f6\fs28\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 Wisconsin v. Yoder, 406 U.S. 205, 234-235, n. 22 (1972)}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 ; }{\f6\fs28\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 Sherbert v. Verner, 374 U.S. 398, 409 (1963)}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 ; }{\f6\fs28\b0\i1\cf1 Zorach v. Clauson, 343 U.S. 306 (1952)}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 , even when the exemption was in no way compelled by the }{\f6\fs28\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 Free Exercise Clause}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 , e.g., }{\f6\fs28\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 Gillette v. United States, 401 U.S. 437 (1971)}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 ; }{\f6\fs28\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 Welsh v. United States, 398 U.S. 333, 371-372 (1970)}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  (WHITE, J., dissenting); }{\f6\fs28\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 Sherbert v. Verner, supra, at 422}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  (Harlan, J., dissenting); }{\f6\fs28\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 Braunfeld v. Brown, 366 U.S. 599, 608 (1961)}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  (dictum); }{\f6\fs28\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 McGowan v. Maryland, 366 U.S. 420, 520 (1961)}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  (opinion of Frankfurter, J.).  }{\f1\fs24\super 4}{\f6\fs18\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 \{\\Scrv_annot \\color=\{\\R=0.682353\\G=0.117647\\B=0.062745\} \\text=Young v. Southwestern Savings & Loan Assn., 509 F.2d 140 (CA5 1975)United States v. Seeger, 380 U.S. 163, 176 (1965)Lemon v. Kurtzman, 403 U.S. 602 (1971)Establishment ClauseWalz v. Tax Comm'n, 397 U.S. 664, 668 (1970\\end_Scrv_annot\}}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "scrivcmt://91FA69ED-9EEB-407C-B86F-C27466898601"}{\fldrslt\f6\fs18\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 )}}{\f1\fs24\super  }{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  If the State does not establish }{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[****48]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  }{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[*91]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  religion over nonreligion by excusing religious practitioners from obligations owed the State, I do not see how the State can be said to establish religion by requiring employers to do the same with respect to obligations owed the employer.  Thus, I think it beyond dispute that the Act does -- and, consistently with the }{\f6\fs28\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 First Amendment}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 , can -- require employers to grant privileges to religious observers as part of the accommodation process.  }
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb200\sl260\slmult0\qj\ltrch\loch {\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[****49]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  II }
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb240\sl260\slmult0\qj\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 Once it is determined that the duty to accommodate sometimes requires that an employee be exempted from an otherwise valid work requirement, the only remaining question is whether this is such }{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[***136]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  a case: Did TWA prove that it exhausted all reasonable accommodations, and that the only remaining alternatives would have caused undue hardship on TWA's business? To pose the question is to answer it, for all that the District Court found TWA had done to accommodate respondent's Sabbath observance was that it "held several meetings with [respondent]\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8230\'85 [and] authorized the union steward to search for someone who would swap shifts." }{\f6\fs28\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 375 F.Supp. 877, 890-891 (WD Mo. 1974)}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 . To conclude that TWA, one of the largest air carriers in the Nation, would have suffered undue hardship had it done anything more defies both reason and common sense.  }
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb200\sl260\slmult0\qj\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 The Court implicitly assumes that the only means of accommodation open to TWA were to compel an unwilling employee to replace Hardison; to pay premium wages to }{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[**2281]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  a voluntary substitute; or to employ one less person during }{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[*92]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  respondent's Sabbath shift.  }{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "scrivcmt://5A9B0148-CECE-483A-BCB8-762BAF9DB3E9"}{\fldrslt\f1\fs24\super 5}}{\f1\fs24\super  }{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  Based on this assumption, the Court seemingly finds}{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[****50]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  that each alternative would have involved undue hardship not only because Hardison would have been given a special privilege, but also because either another employee would have been deprived of rights under the collective-bargaining agreement, ante, at 80-81, or because "more than a de minimis cost," ante, at 84, would have been imposed on TWA.  But the Court's myopic view of the available options is not supported by either the District Court's findings or the evidence adduced at trial.  Thus, the Court's conclusion cannot withstand analysis, even assuming that its rejection of the alternatives it does discuss is justifiable.  }{\f1\fs24\super 6}{\f6\fs18\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 \{\\Scrv_annot \\color=\{\\R=0.682353\\G=0.117647\\B=0.062745\} \\text=375 F.Supp., at 891}
\par\pard\plain \ri0\ql\ltrch\loch {\f6\fs18\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 supra, at 85-\\end_Scrv_annot\}}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "scrivcmt://7BC4F95B-8EFF-47DF-A645-E5678A2C21D1"}{\fldrslt\f6\fs18\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 86}}{\f1\fs24\super  }{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  }
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb240\sl260\slmult0\qj\ltrch\loch {\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[****51]\~\~[*93]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1    To }{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[***137]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  begin with, the record simply does not support the Court's assertion, made without accompanying citations, that "[t]here were no volunteers to relieve Hardison on Saturdays," ante, at 81.  Everett Kussman, the manager of the department in which respondent worked, testified that he had made no effort to find volunteers, App. 136, }{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "scrivcmt://186344BF-7C6F-418F-9A27-B1491AF69D7B"}{\fldrslt\f1\fs24\super 7}}{\f1\fs24\super  }{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  and the union stipulated that its steward had not done so either, }{\f6\fs28\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 id., at 158.  }{\f1\fs24\super 8}{\f1\fs18\b0\i0\ul\ulc0\super\cf4\cb2\highlight2 \{\\Scrv_annot \\color=\{\\R=0.682353\\G=0.117647\\B=0.062745\} \\text=8\~}{\f1\fs18\b0\i0\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 The Court relies, ante, at 78, on the District Court's conclusory assertion that "[a]ny shift or change was impossible within the seniority framework." }{\f6\fs18\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 375 F.Supp., at 889}{\f1\fs18\b0\i0\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 . But the District Court also found that "TWA did not take part in the search for employees willing to swap shifts\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8230\'85 and it was admitted at trial that the Union made no real effort." }{\f6\fs18\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 Id., at 888}{\f1\fs18\b0\i0\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 . Thus, the District Court's statement concerning the impact of "the seniority framework" lends no support to the Court's assertion that there were no volunteers.  See also n. 10, infra.\\end_Scrv_annot\}}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "scrivcmt://268A5113-0D31-4B14-A655-8FA18CE85F0B"}{\fldrslt\f1\fs18\b0\i0\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2  }}{\f1\fs24\super  }{\f6\fs28\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2  }{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[**2282]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  Thus, contrary to the Court's assumption, there may have been one or more employees who, for reasons of either sympathy or personal convenience, willingly would have substituted }{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[*94]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  for respondent on Saturdays until respondent could either regain the non-Saturday shift he had held for the three preceding months }{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "scrivcmt://B1A35BC9-6FDC-4224-A8A3-8B83E1DD75A8"}{\fldrslt\f1\fs24\super 9}}{\f1\fs24\super  }{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  or transfer back to his old department where he had sufficient seniority to avoid Saturday work.  Alternatively, there may have been an employee who preferred respondent's Thursday-Monday daytime shift to his own; in fact, respondent testified that he had informed Kussman and the union steward that the clerk on the Sunday-Thursday night shift (the "graveyard" shift) was dissatisfied with his hours.  }{\f6\fs28\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 Id., at 70}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 .  Thus, }{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[****52]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  respondent's religious observance might have been accommodated by a simple trade of days or shifts without necessarily depriving any employee of his or her contractual rights }{\f1\fs24\super 1}{\f6\fs18\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 \{\\Scrv_annot \\color=\{\\R=0.682353\\G=0.117647\\B=0.062745\} \\text=375 F.Supp., at 884}
\par\pard\plain \ri0\ql\ltrch\loch {\f6\fs18\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 id., at \\end_Scrv_annot\}}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "scrivcmt://8FD1E9DF-13F4-413B-8DA9-2EB80776C84A"}{\fldrslt\f6\fs18\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 144}}{\f1\fs24\super 0 }{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  and without }{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[*95]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  imposing significant }{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[***138]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  costs on TWA.  Of course, it is also possible that no trade -- or none consistent with the seniority system - could have been arranged. But the burden under the EEOC regulation is on TWA to establish that a reasonable accommodation was not possible.  }{\f6\fs28\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 29 CFR \loch\af6\hich\af6\dbch\af6\uc1\u167\'A7 1605.1(c)(1976)}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 .Because it failed either to explore the possibility of a voluntary trade or to assure that its delegate, the union steward, did so, TWA was unable to meet its burden.  }
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb200\sl260\slmult0\qj\ltrch\loch {\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[****53]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  Nor was a voluntary trade the only option open to TWA that the Court ignores; to the contrary, at least two other options are apparent from the record.  First, TWA could have paid overtime to a voluntary replacement for respondent -- assuming that someone would have been willing to work Saturdays for premium pay -- and passed on the cost to respondent.  In fact, one accommodation Hardison suggested would have done just that by requiring Hardison to work overtime when needed at regular pay.  Under this plan, the total overtime cost to the employer -- and the total number of overtime hours available for other employees -- would not have reflected Hardison's Sabbath absences.  Alternatively, TWA could have transferred respondent back to his previous department where he had accumulated substantial seniority, as respondent also suggested.  }{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "scrivcmt://99C7B4A3-BCA0-4C6C-A19B-33F7D25F4EE1"}{\fldrslt\f1\fs24\super 1}}{\f1\fs24\super 1 }{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  Admittedly, both options would have violated the collective-bargaining agreement; the former because the agreement required that employees working over 40 hours per week receive premium pay, and the latter because the agreement prohibited employees from transferring }{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[*96]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  departments }{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[**2283]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  more than once every six months.  But neither}{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[****54]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  accommodation would have deprived any other employee of rights under the contract or violated the seniority system in any way.  }{\f1\fs24\super 1}{\f6\fs18\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 \{\\Scrv_annot \\color=\{\\R=0.682353\\G=0.117647\\B=0.062745\} \\text=Draper v. United States Pipe & Foundry Co., 527 F.2d 515 (CA6 1975\\end_Scrv_annot\}}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "scrivcmt://3FC4B53F-1781-4690-9131-8D6442858A95"}{\fldrslt\f6\fs18\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 )}}{\f1\fs24\super 2 }{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  Plainly an employer cannot avoid his duty to accommodate by signing a contract that precludes all reasonable accommodations; even the Court appears to concede as much, ante, at 79.  Thus I do not believe it can be even seriously argued that TWA would have suffered "undue hardship" to its business had it required respondent to pay the extra costs of his replacement, or had it transferred respondent to his former department.  }{\f1\fs24\super 1}{\f6\fs18\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 \{\\Scrv_annot \\color=\{\\R=0.682353\\G=0.117647\\B=0.062745\} \\text=Establishment Clausesupra, at 90Selective Draft Law Cases, 245 U.S. 366, 389-390 (1918)Gallagher v. Crown Kosher Market, 366 U.S. 617, 627 (1961\\end_Scrv_annot\}}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "scrivcmt://7D8CE15C-6484-4CB7-9B28-69A620847573"}{\fldrslt\f6\fs18\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 )}}{\f1\fs24\super 3 }{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  }
\par\plain {\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[****55]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  What }{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[***139]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  makes today's decision most tragic, however, is not that respondent Hardison has been needlessly deprived of his livelihood simply because he chose to follow the dictates of his conscience.  Nor is the tragedy exhausted by the impact it will have on thousands of Americans like Hardison who could be forced to live on welfare as the price they must pay for }{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[*97]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  worshiping their God.  }{\f1\fs24\super 1}{\f6\fs18\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 \{\\Scrv_annot \\color=\{\\R=0.682353\\G=0.117647\\B=0.062745\} \\text=Sherbert v. Verner, 374 U.S. 398 (1963\\end_Scrv_annot\}}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "scrivcmt://D9D5C67D-3CDD-4455-A9D8-ACB2F98F4638"}{\fldrslt\f6\fs18\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 )}}{\f1\fs24\super 4 }{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  The ultimate tragedy is that despite Congress' best efforts, one of this Nation's pillars of strength -- our hospitality to religious diversity -- has been seriously eroded.  All Americans will be a little poorer until today's decision is erased.  }
\par\plain {\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~[****56]\~}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  I respectfully dissent.  }
